Introduction¶

FordGo is a regional public bicycle sharing system in California's San Francisco Bay Area. It is operated by Motivate in a partnership with the Metropolitan Transportation Commission and the Bay Area Air Quality Management District. Bay Wheels is 'the first regional and large-scale bicycle sharing system deployed in California and on the West Coast of the United States. It was established as Bay Area Bike Share in August 2013. the system was officially re-launched as Ford GoBike in a partnership with Ford Motor Company. After Motivate's acquisition by Lyft, the system was renamed to Bay Wheels on June 11, 2019.

This data set includes 2,390,220 information about individual rides made in the bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area for the year of 2019

Quality Issues¶

  • start time is datetime datatype not object
  • end time is datetime datatype not object
  • null values in start_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id, end_station_name, member_birth_year and member_gender columns.
  • member_gender is category data type not string
  • user_type should be category datatype
  • bike_share_for_all_trip should also be a category datatype
  • duplicate values
  • no column for bike_share_for_all_trip in the month of december
  • duration should be in minutes
  • there should be a column for weekends

Further Cleaning¶

Define¶

creating a column for trip time of day from start time¶
In [8]:
idx = pd.DatetimeIndex(df_['start_time'])
ilocs = np.arange(len(df_))

conds = [np.in1d(ilocs, idx.indexer_between_time('03:00:00', '11:00:00', include_start=False, include_end=True)),
         np.in1d(ilocs, idx.indexer_between_time('11:00:00', '17:00:00', include_start=False, include_end=True))]

choices = ['early', 'mid-day']

df_['trip_time_of_day'] = np.select(conds, choices, default='late')

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 2,390,220 entries in the dataset with 15 columns. which holds information such as

  • bike_id, start_time of trip
  • end_time of tripe
  • duration
  • station_id etc.

variables are numeric, category, string and date_time. After cleaning, the data became 2,371,857 with additional columns;

  • trip_time_of_day
  • start_month
  • time_diff
  • is_weekend

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

i am most interested in when most trips taken in terms of time of day or month of the year?

How long does the average trip take? and does this depend on if the user is a subscriber or a customer?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

i expect that user_type will have big effect on how long average trips take; if the user is a customer or a subscriber. i also expect tha weekend will affect when trips are taken in terms of day

Conclusions¶

when are most trips taken in terms of time of day or month of the year?

for this question, i made a barchart and a piechart which showed in percentage when most trips are taken in terms of time of day and most trips(37.3%) are taken late hours(from 5pm-3am) this was arrived at by splitting the start_time to represent early(from 3am-11am), mid-day(from 11am-5pm) and late(from 5pm-3am)

for weekday, i made a label column for days of the week and represented the day name of the start_time column with this label, then plotted a chart to show it, it appears that thursdays and tuesdays are busiest days.

and as for month, apparently the month of march is the busiest, i just plotted the column i extracted from start_time column which represented the month of each trip

How long does the average trip take? and does this depend on if the user is a subscriber or a customer?

As shown above, the average duration for customers is 16.40446mins while that of subscribers is 10.571688mins. so customers on average take longer trips than subscribers

and appearently, most users are subscribers which is 80.7% of the total bike users
